{
  "reasoning": "To calculate the value of a European put option on a currency, I'll use the Garman-Kohlhagen model (modified Black-Scholes for currency options). The formula for a put option is: P = K*e^(-r_d*T)*N(-d2) - S*e^(-r_f*T)*N(-d1), where d1 = [ln(S/K) + (r_d - r_f + σ²/2)*T] / (σ*√T) and d2 = d1 - σ*√T. Given: S = 0.52 (current exchange rate), K = 0.50 (strike price), σ = 0.12 (volatility), r_d = 0.04 (domestic risk-free rate), r_f = 0.08 (foreign risk-free rate), T = 8/12 = 0.6667 years. Step 1: Calculate d1. d1 = [ln(0.52/0.50) + (0.04 - 0.08 + 0.12²/2)*0.6667] / (0.12*√0.6667). ln(0.52/0.50) = ln(1.04) = 0.0392. (r_d - r_f + σ²/2) = 0.04 - 0.08 + 0.0072 = -0.0328. -0.0328 * 0.6667 = -0.0219. Numerator = 0.0392 - 0.0219 = 0.0173. σ*√T = 0.12 * 0.8165 = 0.0980. d1 = 0.0173 / 0.0980 = 0.177. Step 2: Calculate d2. d2 = d1 - σ*√T = 0.177 - 0.0980 = 0.079. Step 3: Find N(-d1) and N(-d2). N(-0.177) = 0.4298. N(-0.079) = 0.4685. Step 4: Calculate put value. P = K*e^(-r_d*T)*N(-d2) - S*e^(-r_f*T)*N(-d1). e^(-0.04*0.6667) = e^(-0.0267) = 0.9737. e^(-0.08*0.6667) = e^(-0.0533) = 0.9481. P = 0.50 * 0.9737 * 0.4685 - 0.52 * 0.9481 * 0.4298. P = 0.2281 - 0.2119 = 0.0162.",
